# 12. Detection Workflow

Regional degradation patterns, failed recovery stabilization, dependency propagation visibility, or survivability risk indicators initiate resilience-oriented operational coordination workflows.

Resilience escalation occurs only after recovery workflows determine that localized restoration is insufficient to preserve distributed operational survivability.

Detection does not immediately imply failover. It initiates resilience coordination review.

## Detection Flow

    Regional Degradation Detection
    → Recovery Stabilization Review
    → Survivability Risk Evaluation
    → Resilience Coordination Review
    → Failover Readiness Assessment

---

# 13. Resilience Coordination Logic

Distributed failover workflows are initiated only after recovery validation confirms that localized intervention cannot preserve regional survivability.

The coordination workflow validates routing stability, dependency continuity, failover propagation safety, and survivability visibility before distributed transition execution begins.

Resilience coordination remains technical and operational. Enterprise continuity governance, executive escalation, and business continuity ownership remain Level-5 responsibilities.

## Resilience Decision Boundaries

| Required Before Distributed Failover | Not Sufficient Alone |
|---|---|
| Localized recovery insufficiency | Single regional alert |
| Route convergence readiness | Unverified routing assumption |
| Dependency continuity visibility | Isolated service health check |
| Failover propagation safety | Manual operator confidence |
| Survivability evidence readiness | Unvalidated dashboard state |

---

# 14. Distributed Resilience Workflow

![Workflow Overview](./diagrams/workflow-overview.png)

## Resilience Flow

    Regional Degradation Detection
    → Resilience Coordination Logic
    → Distributed Failover Activation
    → Dependency-Aware Failover Sequencing
    → Route Convergence Validation
    → Dependency Continuity Review
    → Regional Survivability Validation
    → Evidence Aggregation
    → Resilience Confirmation

## Workflow Description

The workflow begins when regional degradation or failed recovery stabilization indicates that local recovery alone is insufficient.

Distributed failover coordination evaluates whether failover can proceed without amplifying regional impact, destabilizing routing, or collapsing downstream dependencies.

Route convergence validation confirms that traffic transition is stable. Dependency continuity review confirms that dependent services remain technically operational after the distributed transition.

This workflow intentionally excludes enterprise continuity escalation, executive governance coordination, and organizational continuity reporting.

## Operational Decision Points

| Decision Point | Operator Question | Expected Evidence |
|---|---|---|
| Resilience Escalation Review | Is localized recovery insufficient? | Recovery validation evidence |
| Failover Coordination Review | Can distributed failover occur safely? | Failover coordination evidence |
| Route Stabilization Review | Did routing converge correctly after failover? | Route convergence evidence |
| Dependency Continuity Review | Will dependent services remain operational? | Dependency continuity evidence |
| Survivability Review | Is technical continuity preserved? | Survivability validation evidence |
| Lifecycle Boundary Review | Was L5 enterprise continuity intentionally excluded? | Lifecycle purity evidence |

